up|29|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The main question is how the hand should be played. Assuming clubs behave, declarer has 5 clubs, 2 spades and 1 heart for sure. So declarer needs one extra trick. She knows that hearts are breaking 6-2 after the 3rd heart trick. So if possible, East must be kept off the lead.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Also it was reasonable for declarer to hope West had the @DA. If that were the case, declarer can set up a 9th trick in diamonds. Another chance was if East had the @SQ. In that case declarer can take 3 spade tricks. |
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And even if the spade finesse loses, declarer can still hope that West has the @DA. It's a matter of giving yourself two 50% chances instead of one.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Next, lets talk about East. If I were East I would have made a ^*b DONT double ^*n ^*g:dont::Competitive Bidding, (LINK  -  DONT)^*n with my one suited hand in hearts. 6 card suit, 9 HCP 6-3-3-1 distribution is more than enough to compete over 1NT especially not vul.|

