nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let me briefly explain about Puppet Stayman. Puppet Stayman, which is a reasonable convention over 2N in particular allows you to discover if partner has either a 4-card major or a 5-card major. The way it works I would bid 3@C. Partner bids 3@H or 3@S with a 5-card suit. With one or two 4-card majors partner bids 3@D. |
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And finally, with no 4-card major partner bids 3NT. So on this hand, if I chose to bid 3@C and we were playing Puppet Stayman partner would bid 3N (no 4 or 5 card major) and I would not be able to find out if we had a 5-3 spade fit). |
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If I chose to transfer to spades by bidding 3@H then we would miss a 4-4 heart fit. So I have to make a choice. But playing regular Stayman I can bid 3@C and over 3@D bid 3@S. Then partner knows I have 4 hearts and 5 spades and can place the contract. |
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Similarly, if I bid 3@H over 3@D that shows 5 hearts and 4 spades. So although Puppet Stayman is preferred by a majority of better players, it does have some flaws. Personally, I have no preference about whether or not to play it.|
