mb|P|mb|2C|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|That is a reasonable 2@C opener, but let me discuss the downside. Whenever you open 2@C when diamonds is your suit, you are going to have a problem auction. It is going to start 2@C-2@D-3@D which has some severe downsides. One is you have "self-preempted" in that you are at 3@D before you make your first natural bid. So you are quite high.|
PG| ***** 69 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The 2nd is, the contract is probably being played from the wrong side if you end up in diamonds. So, you should be reluctant to open 2@C when your suit is diamonds. Although with the North hand it is reasonable. I might consider opening 1@D even with such a nice hand. But a hand with 6 quick tricks is so rare that I think 2@C is best.|
PG| ***** 70 ***** |


mb|P|mb|2D|mb|P|mb|3D|mb|P|nt|^z@3^b@2^^|cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now just to illustrate a special kind of Blackwood we are going to play ^*b Kickback Blackwood^*N  
^*g:kickback::Slam Bidding,(LINK  -  Kickback)^*n  on this hand. The way it works is, 1 suit higher than the trump suit is how you bid Roman Key Card. So 4NT is RKCB for spades, 4@S is RKCB for hearts, 4@H is RKCB for diamonds, and 4@D is RKCB for clubs. |

